snippet.textDisplay: Anyone thinking "It's capitalism", it's not. And I think that was the point, it's us people, everyday people. We just live in an age where responsibilities are shifted like bad las vegas roulette table. Todays climate change is the result of the I and II. industrial revolution (It takes 10 -50 years for CO2 to rise in the upper layers of atmosphere.)  Long before marxism, communism or capitalism, the effects of our irresponsibilities will  be visible in about 50-100 yrs. All of the regimes, conspiracy theories, God, they are all just placeholders and buckets where we put are complete lack if responsibility and pass it on to these symbolics. Like pie said, ppl want McDonalds, Jeeps, and light 24 -7, in the mean time they want to tell anyone not farming sea weed they are the problem. So I say Climate Change is the best thing that can happen to humans. You want global? Well now you have global responsibilities. Can't solve them? Ppl will die globally in droves, governments will collapse, wars will ensue, and hard times will follow creating hard people. It's Darwinism at it's best. Having said that I'm not a cynic I'm deeply optimistic and believe humans will survive, but our civilisation as we know it won't. You don't like it? Stop eating burgers, don't drive 100 meters to the store, don't drive up and down the escalator, your legs have been evolving for 1,2 millions years and they can get you anywhere on the planet. So fucking use them. Don't feel like it? then R.I.P. No government will teach kids to take out the trash, exercise, be healthy or eat properly, that is your individual fucking responsibility, otherwise? Welcome to CCCP where you do what you are told to do. Cheers ;)

snippet.textDisplay:
Beautiful job on this one. I enjoyed the added polish on the production and it also added a few more shades to Pie's character. I liked that during the compulsory Pie-rant, he's declaring at the top of his lungs that saving the planet one clam at a time is a waste of time and then in the next scene he's walking the shoreline picking up litter... one piece of plastic at a time.

I would never want Tom to abandon the one man/one camera (/one ear piece ;)) "at the scene" reporting motif that has given this character so much momentum, but it would be awesome if he could do more features like this.

snippet.textDisplay:
Try it, you might like it? Mr J. Pie.
Like many foraged foods, seaweed emerged from the wilderness to capture the imagination of Britain's celebrity chefs. It has long been prized in Japan, where it is as commonplace as egg and chips. The Japanese have got it right: seaweed is a delicious, versatile and extraordinarily healthy food. It will also fill you up; a breakfast that includes seaweed will keep all but the most habitual snacker off the biscuits until lunchtime.
